keto sushi edition

>Who is /fat/ for?
For stoic stuffing-eaters who are working towards a better physique through meaningful hard-work, strategy, and dedication. This is not QTDDTOT, stick to questions on fat loss. Post height and weight when asking for advice.
Join our Fatty Contest: https://www.fattycontest.com/

>What do I do first?
1. Read https://physiqonomics.com/fat-loss/
2. Calculate your Body Fat Percentage: https://fitness.bizcalcs.com/Calculator.asp?Calc=Body-Fat-Navy
3. Calculate your TDEE: https://www.sailrabbit.com/bmr/
Remember to use bodyfat% and use Katch-McArdle Formula with sedentary settings or your TDEE will be too high.
4. Plan your weight loss: https://www.losertown.org/eats/cal.php
5. Track your nutrition with MyFitnessPal (better for packaged food), Cronometer (better for generic food/macros) or LoseIt (great for both).

>Now what?
Count calories, all of them.
Eat about 500-1000 less calories than your TDEE.
Buy scales, be accurate.
Learn to cook. Try to stick to lean protein and green vegetables.
Eat a lot of protein. 0.72g per lb of goal lean body mass.
Doing cardio, even just walking, will improve your health. There is no such thing as a healthy fat heart, but you can offset the risks.
Lifting weights will keep and gain muscle mass and burn fat much quicker. No lifting results in the body burning away muscle AND fat.
Drink more water.
Read the /fit/ sticky: https://liamrosen.com/fitness.html

>DON'T
Eat refined sugars, they're terrible for you regardless of calories.
Eat processed foods.
Drink your calories (alcohol, soda, starbucks).
Freak out over a weight loss stall. Plateaus can last up to three weeks.
"Reward" yourself. Cheat days cheat only yourself.

>Other resources:
Loose skin, gyno & stretch marks: https://weight-loss-side-effects.netlify.app/
Reddit wiki: https://www.reddit.com/r/loseit/wiki/faq

OMAD to start - the first chart. I've done that (sort of) since high school, so I'm used to it and don't get hungry. I got fat because I started grazing all fucking day, even though I only ate dinner, and it was all terrible food.

A month or so ago I was kind of sticking around 211 so I adjusted my TDEE calc from light activity to sedentary to bust through. I also switched up my meals to get more protein, as I realized I wasn't getting nearly enough. And I have a snack around 11 am (plain greek yogurt and a little bit of honey) now.

Meals initially were either two sandwiches or six scrambled eggs, or one sandwich and three scrambled eggs. Plus a bunch of vegetables on the side (spinach, tomatoes, carrots, sugar snap or snow peas). Meals now are chicken, cottage cheese, hard-boiled eggs and a big salad (same vegetables, just now in a bowl with a little balsamic vinaigrette).

The "breakfast" and "other" calories on almost all of those days are creamer I put in coffee. Sunday I ate lunch with family, and pigged out because why not. So I just rough guessed the amount there.

No real exercise for most of the time, other than walking my dogs 30-60 minutes a day, which I have always done, even as a fatass. Maybe two months ago I started rowing and doing pullups/chinups and hanging leg raises every day, plus one of pushups, goblet squats, or OHP+lateral raise with kettle bells. I stopped rowing because my back is fucked from the military and it isn't helping though. I just do a set of each exercise a few times throughout the day during breaks from work (WFH). Just getting my body used to exercising again before I start lifting heavier after I'm done losing weight.

Track calories, take a set of measurements every week: weight and body fat from scale, circumference of gut and neck (for military BF measure), and four pictures (front, back, both profiles).

And that's about it really.

When I'm really hungry I make one of these with 3 eggs and a couple slices of diced spam
Just cook the noodles then drain the majority of the water out, then add the flavoring, and ingredients and let it simmer for a few minutes until cooked.
It's good.

Another thing I like to make is I'll cook a couple slices of toast, then spread cottage cheese over it, add some sliced jalapenos on top, then sprinkle on some mozarella and grill it until golden.

Another good way to cook eggs is tamagoyaki, although it requires a special rectangular frying pan to do well
I like to crack 3 eggs into the pan with a little lubrication to stop it from burning, then scramble them, let it cook a little bit, then liberally apply mozarella on top, then roll it.
Cheese stuffed egg roll, it's good.
Can add spring onions to the mix for added flavor, or really whatever you want, maybe some bacon?

Something that I'd make a lot when I was a kid was banana protein shakes
I didn't have protein powder at the time, so I used raw eggs instead, but essentially it's just a protein shake made from milk and banana protein powder, then blended with a real banana or two.
It's pretty filling for what it is

>>69479551
>Fasting will slow down your metabolism
No. My metabolism remains unchanged from when I started 6 months ago. If anything, it has increased slightly.
>increase stress
Yes, it increases cortisol.
>destroy gains
Nope. Been fasting for the past 6 months and I haven't lost any gains. The worst thing that has happened is that certain lifts have stagnated, but that's all, and I'm aware that my strength will return to me when I go back to eating normally. However, some lifts have actually increased and have been completely unaffected by my fasting. And for me, that's still worth the trade-off for fast fat loss. So, yeah, no muscle loss from me, and that's due to the fact that fasting increases your growth hormone production to preserve your muscles and prevent/minimize muscles loss.
>make you age faster
Actually, the opposite has been shown to be true due to the massive increase in autophagy and growth hormone production.
>decrease sleep quality
Correct. In my personal experience, when fasting I usually only sleep for around 4-6 hours and it's hard to even get to sleep in the first place, even after taking magnesium or things that aid in sleep. So, yes, you are correct about that.

I like dinner to be my largest meal and make damn sure it’s got carbs. >>69473576
Starting out from nothing means your muscles and joints aren't developed.
Also, your mind isn't developed. Running isn't comfortable. The reward is in how good you feel after you're done (though for the first few weeks you don't get this good feeling) and in improved general fitness (walking is easier, moving is easier, getting up is easier, etc.)
So two things:
-build up your physical fitness
-build up your mental toughness. The mentality is this: when you think you're done, you're 30% of the way into your jog. Learn to push through the pain and do a few more minutes.

posts.com: People think as you start working out, you need more and more volume to make gains - it's partially true but people think this is the case indefinitely. Rat terrier

The rat terrier was the most common breed of dog in the US prior to industrialized farming. They were bred as a farm dog companion that doubled as a rat-killing machine (rat infestations can be serious issues on farms, and these guys will kill dozens of given the chance).

They have one of the strongest pair bonds of any breed, not to a family, but to a single person. They’re a great size, roughly 18lbs (my little guy is 14 and my big boy is 25, neither of which is out of the ordinary). They have an average lifespan of 16 years, and are very healthy throughout old age.

I wouldn’t be surprised if the breed takes off in popularity. It’s still kind of rare, but its size, health, and demeanor make for a great pet.

Pic is Felixeville’s Traveller, the most awarded ratty in the AKC, so an excellent example. They come in a huge variety of color patterns, with piebald being the most common.

>>69476257
Please ignore the keto schizo, he literally stalks threads and does nothing but talk about how carbs are evil and keto is the only way to accomplish anything fitness related.
As for MY OPINION on carbs: most people eat too many of them, and especially eat too many of the worst kind of carbs, which are sugars, but carbs are VERY IMPORTANT to your diet. Carbs are split between three general types, which are sugars, starches and fiber. Try to avoid sugars (though fruits are good for you and have alot of sugar), these are often not good nutritionally and they'll spike your blood sugar which when it levels out will cause you to become hungry. Starches are often nutritionally good for you, but they're like sugars and can spike your blood sugar as well, this would be things like rice and potatoes. There's nothing wrong with eating them, just be aware that they can cause problems with hunger as well. Finally, fiber, which is slow to digest and pretty much always a good idea to eat. Lots of vegetables are high in fiber, like broccoli, cabbage, spinach, etc. You should try to get as many of your carbs from fiber as possible.
General diet plan: hit your protein intake goal and then fill out the rest of your calories with fat and carbs, and try to get the *good* kinds of fat and carbs. Cutting out fat is very bad for you as many important vitamins require fat for your body to properly absorb them (fat-soluble vitamins). Cutting out carbs probably isn't as damaging to your health as cutting out fats, but carbs are the most efficient fuel source for your body and cutting them out will be difficult and it will also probably make you feel like shit (if you're eating good carbs, that is).

personal finance:
budgeting: you should definitely look into zero-based budgeting (ZBB). There's a lot of apps/tools/spreadsheets you can use to budget this way, the most popular being YNAB (You Need A Budget).
taxes: take the standard deduction (assuming you're US)
debt: you need to pay off ALL of your debt ASAP (not including mortgage if you have one) (priority #0)
saving: have an emergency fund that can cover your expenses for 6 months (priority #1)
investing: If you're in a good job, you should take advantage of employer 401k matching first. Then Roth IRA. Then a standard brokerage account. invest in indexes, mutual funds. A beta of 1 with the market means you're basically investing in a balanced, diverse portfolio with performance strongly correlated with the market overall. I highly recommend you self manage your money rather than pawning it off to a hack "mutual fund expert". Buy and never sell. Don't panic if goes down. DO NOT TRY TO TIME (or beat) THE MARKET.
investing in real estate: only invest in one primary residence for yourself. don't fall for "alpha landlord" facebook tier "grindset". Investing in real estate is not some easy hack to become rich.
